    "message": "\nI'm sure I'm not telling you anything you haven't heard or read before.\n\nRe: your biology career, not much I can say about that. Re: music, I think you're getting too much into your head and thinking about the results and whether or not people will be listening to your work tomorrow or 100 years from now. If possible, try to get in touch with your love of the process and let go of what happens after that. \n\nI'm pretty sure it was an interview with Van Morrison where they asked him if he ever went back and listened to his previous albums, and his response was an adamant no. He had enjoyed the process of writing those songs, but once it was done, he was focused on the process of writing the next batch of songs.\n\nAgain, it's a lot easier said than done to get in touch with the process and the love of doing and divorce yourself from what happens afterwards. But I think if you read biographies of any famous or semi-famous creatives, they will ultimately say the same thing at some point - they love the process of doing and creating and after that it's out of their hands as to how people might respond.\n\nJust my 2 cents anyway.\n\nCheers,",
