    "message": "\nHi {{ name }},\n\nYour post really resonated with me. I'm not sure if my advice is much\n\nhelp but I also recently turned 30 and had some similar thoughts.\n\nOn one hand, you're almost surely correct: Very few humans will\n\naccomplish something of the scale you described (a lasting record,\n\nremembered by humanity).\n\nOn the other hand, I think there are two easy approaches.\n\n1) Start volunteering or giving back in some interactive way on a\n\nsmall, maybe local scale. Find a homeless shelter or soup kitchen or\n\nthe EFF or whatever piques your interest and you will feel like you're\n\nmaking a small difference, which could feel like a huge improvement.\n\nIt's a bit of a mental trick, right? You may feel better, but you also\n\nmay never make a dent in the universe (even though you'll surely be\n\nfondly remembered by many you helped).\n\n2) Write down the biggest problems in the world as you see it, figure\n\nout who is working on them, get in touch with them, don't settle for\n\nanything less than working on the most serious, world-changing project\n\nyou can possibly get involved with (it may only tangentially involve\n\nyour current career skill set). Go big, cast wide, expect rejection,\n\nbut genuine enthusiasm for a noble cause may get you further into a\n\ncommunity of world-class Doers than you think. And then you're one of\n\nthem.\n\nI think (1) is objectively pretty easy but many people don't get\n\naround to it, it gets lost in the daily grind of work and play. I\n\nthink (2) is outrageously difficult, but you should strongly consider\n\nit before you turn 40. Don't have this conversation with yourself\n\nagain in 10 years, if you value your happiness.\n\n(3) Make the next Snapchat, cash out, buy an island, volcano lair,\n\nrobot army. You know, the usual SF hacker dream.\n\nGood luck,",
