    "message": "\n\nHi {{ name }}-  thanks for your post. \n\nThis is the first listserve I have responded to, maybe it is of some use to\n\nyou.  Maybe not.  \n\nI am 42.  When I entered college, I intended to major in physics and\n\nphilosophy in the interest of having all keys to the world of knowledge.\n\nAlas, my math skills ended my physics path, and the philosophy track became\n\ntoo theoretical and un-rooted for me.  I switched over to a Tibetan Buddhist\n\nstudies track.  \n\nLeaving college, I cooked professionally.  Religion doesn't pay the bills\n\nyou know.\n\nI pursued a degree in Chinese Medicine (philosophy in action) and practiced\n\nfor a decade (still do part time).  I took a job managing a book business\n\n(in my 5th year now) because it pays well.  The work is fine.  \n\nSo where does that leave me?  In a career that I will probably stick with\n\nbecause it is pleasant enough and I am starting to live comfortably, but was\n\nnever my intended goal.  I am married, and have two kids, and that\n\ndefinitely gives some meaning to the day (though not always feeling like\n\nit).  I like still practicing acupuncture because it helps the people I\n\ntreat.  \n\nI think age may come reliably with a dulling of that youthful drive to\n\nchange the world.  SO many goals have come and gone, but they are not\n\nfailures but rather changes of tack.  Odds are now very much against my\n\nbecoming a kung fu master, and I can live with that.  I will not learn\n\nChinese in my lifetime I am pretty sure.  It is all ok.  Short of acts of\n\nmegalomania, you can affect only those immediately around you (which is not\n\nnothing, mind you).   There is no straight line to destiny.\n\nFind love where you can.  Find enjoyment In what you do.  You may find that\n\nis meaning enough.  It may be that is all there is to it, and that is kind\n\nof fantastic too. ",
