    "subject": "Re: [The Listserve] Life without meaning",
    "tags": [
      "Altruism"
    ],
    "message": " \n\nI know you were hoping for responses from the \"more experienced\" crowd, but hear me out for a moment. You don't really have much to lose.\n\n \n\nWhen I was younger, I wanted to be a professional tennis player. Eventually, I realized it wasn't feasible as a steady career.\n\nThen in high school, I got good grades in economics. So people told me to pursue economics in university. And I did, because why not?\n\n \n\nTurns out I'm not a very good economist.\n\n \n\nEventually I settled on Business Marketing. Although this isn't the most useless major one could pursue in undergrad, I can hardly use it to change the world like a biochemist could use theirs.\n\n \n\nI know one thing I want to do with my life is start a NPO for young adults with disordered eating issues. I suffered from disordered eating (I can't actually say 'eating disorder' because the medical definition requires someone to be underweight -- and although I partook in starving and purging and plenty of other horrible habits, I never quite reached 'underweight'. I did try, though, and it almost killed me a half dozen times), so this issue is personal to me. This is a big challenge for someone of any age. But I still want to try because I know if someone had reached out to me sooner, they might've spared me several miserable years of self-hatred. I don't know that I'll change a life -- but I can always hope and I can definitely try. Right now I just reach out to young adults on an individual, word-of-mouth (or whatever the internet version of that is) basis. It doesn't always work, but sometimes it does help. I don't know how marketing is going to help me achieve it, but who knows? Maybe I'll use my skills to create awareness about the issue and hopefully save a few lives.\n\n \n\nI never would have expected that this is something I would've wanted to do with my life. I never thought I could change people's lives just by listening, emphasizing, and urging them towards the path to recovery. I feel extremely lucky that I've been recovered for a record length now -- almost 9 months. It doesn't seem like much, but I spent the entire previous year falling off the recovery wagon and  climbing back on. I don't change the world with what I do. And honestly, what I do won't matter in a few hundred millenia. But it's important to the person I'm reaching out to. It chanes their world. And that's all that matters to me.\n\n \n\nMaybe rethink what you want to actually change. Nobody is saying you have to give up your dreams. Just rethink how you can use your passions (or skills, or knowledge, whatever) to come at them from a different angle.\n\n \n\nGood luck!",
    "cleaned": true,
    "title": "I'm Not A Very Good Economist",
    "quote": "Maybe rethink what you want to actually change",
    "position": 50
