    "message": "\n{{ name }},\n\nI understand that ups and downs with career choices and desires may lead you to feel this way over time. I am not sure what weight my little nugget of advice will have, but here it goes: try to go down to the roots of your passion for biology and music. What was it that made you so intrigued by these subjects and want to contribute to the field? When I think back on what turned me on to my career in public policy, I remember the teachers I had that truly ignited my interest in and passion for creating positive change. Now, not all of these teachers were social studies teachers who taught me about government and civics. These were teachers, many of whom decided to devote their lives to teaching a subject about which they were truly passionate, and make a change in their students' lives. One of my greatest teachers and role models was my high school physics teacher -- I had no interest in the subject, but he was determined to help me learn and understand the concepts in a way that which inspired me to work hard and try to make that kind of difference in another person's life.\n\nI suppose what I am trying to ask is this: have you considered a career in teaching? You could still pursue your interests while creating a legacy for future generations of students. You might ignite in them a passion for creating music, or an interest in biology. Your teaching style may excite them so that even though they might not be interested in your particular subject, they will be motivated to learn more and change the world. \n\nBest of luck in your future endeavors, whatever they may be!",
