    "message": "\nHey {{ name }},\n\nI am 23 years old and already relate in many ways to your sentiments.  The reality is that our contemporary society has discarded vocation for career, and so we live, we work, and we play as domesticated animals.\n\nIn some ways, that is exactly what we are, but if we were to accept this reality a priori then we would be thumbing our noses at centuries of inspiration in philosophy, science, and the arts.  We would be negating the urgency and the poignancy of the question that you yourself are faced with now.\n\nI don't think it is a \"terrible\" outlook.  I think it's honest.  We as people need to see our true reflections,  past the funhouse mirrors that society erects so that we may adhere to normative ideals of beauty, success, and a life fulfilled. \n\nHappiness is not what we should be striving for.  Our contemporary search for happiness thus far has given us happy pills.  That's not what I'm looking for, and I doubt what you are looking for. \n\nI never respond to these things, but I feel compelled to because I myself feel like an observer.\n\nPsychoanalysis has helped me cope with this sense of  hopelessness, along with art, good food, physical activity, getting away from the computer, breathing deep breaths from the belly, live music, and spontaneity.  \n\nI still feel rather hopeless, but hopeful to know that I am not alone in my hopelessness.  You are not alone in your hopelessness....and maybe it's not hopelessness for you, but rather something more positive. ",
