    "message": "\nHi {{ name }},\n\nIt's true. Sooner or later, everything you accomplish will be forgotten. No one will be around to remember you or your works.\n\nI see two paths toward solving your philosophical dilemma. The choice between them depends on your personality and inclinations. \n\nIf you consider yourself open to spiritual considerations, I would suggest reading the Bhagavad Gita. The protagonist of that story, a warrior approaching a pointless battle with an enemy that included his own kinsmen, felt an emptiness and sense of uselessness that is very similar to what you describe yourself as feeling.\n\nIf you are not religious and do not consider yourself particularly spiritual, I would suggest reading the existentialists, particularly Camus (\"The Myth of Sisyphus\" and other essays). He tackled the question of how to act in the absence of God, in a universe that seems to provide no meaning.\n\nMy own opinion arises from the observation that most historical solutions to the question of human purpose, whether grounded in religion or simply in ethics, revolve around how we treat other people. \"Be kinder\" is what most systems of meaning boil down to.\n\nBut what could be more ephemeral than kindness? What trace does it leave? Still, this is what the world's wisest recommend.\n\nI believe that, as creatures bound by time, our purpose is to act within the time we are given, without thought to legacy or posterity. Imagine you are on a sinking ship, with no hope of rescue. You cannot save yourself or others; only your own behavior until the end is under your control. \n\nDo you sit alone and contemplate your dilemma until the waves cover your head?\n\nOr do you comfort your fellow passengers (children, the terrified) as best you can, and go down hand in hand?\n\nWe are all in the same boat.\n\nGood luck to you!",
    "cleaned": true,
    "title": "Bound By Time",
    "quote": "What could be more ephemeral than kindness?",
    "position": 91
