    "message": "\nI know exactly how you feel.  I put a lot of effort into school and had great grades, got a fantastic job, and then realized that it wasn't what I wanted to do at all.  I have completely redefined my life since then.  Sometimes I am still sad and mourn the loss of the life I thought I would have, but I really enjoy what I am doing now and have found meaning in smaller things.   I spend a lot of time loving people, contributing to my community, and caring for my family and friends.  Over time I have seen lots of rewards from this that I don't think I would see from my job.  It isn't far-reaching at first, but the more people you are kind to, the more effort you put into your community... I don't know.  All those people you touch reach out and touch others.  Putting positive energy out there starts a perpetual pay-it-forward system.  Helping people who need it, being kind to those who struggle; it adds so much to the world.  \n\nAnd yes, I think it does have to do with age, into my 20's I was so full of energy and I believed I could do anything, but every choice closes off a different option and eventually, you are on a path and it usually doesn't involve saving the world.  You realize you can only affect a small bubble around yourself.  Also I think there is a biological component too, like a second puberty.  In women in manifests with wishing for babies, in men, it manifests in the feeling to settle and contribute, I think.  ( I don't know, I am a woman. )\n\nAnyway, that is my train of thought after reading your post.",
