    "message": "\n{{ name }},\n\nWhile I find your observation and position on life (and age) interesting, I also find them a bit naive and close minded.\n\nTime obliterates everything.\n\nTo say you won't create any kind of music that will last over a hundred years as a reason not to do it is ridiculous. Nothing created in this lifetime or any other should be made to sustain forever, or for even a long amount of time. Creation isn't for history, it's for you. Make your music because it brings you happiness or satisfaction, not because it will \"change the world\". Some of the greatest musicians/composers in all the world are barely \"hundreds\" of years old and millions of artists that are also amazing have already been \"forgotten\". With technology ever-changing, simply having a song in iTunes could potentially make it last \"forever\" anyways, and what does that mean... probably nothing. Suppose someone from years down the road hears your song, and has their world \"changed\", boom; you've changed the world. That could also happen tomorrow, or next year. But more importantly YOUR world would be changed because you created the song to begin with. \n\nI think you've latched on to the meaning of life being about what you do. In reality, it's about why you do them.\n\nAlexander the great had this same ideology about life, and eventually the history of the world won't have space for him in it either. Every year, old events are taken out of history books, and new ones are added in; this is exactly the way the history of the world works, everything is condensed until it is omitted.\n\nSo remember:\n\nChange one persons world and you have \"changed the world\". But more importantly, change your own.\n\nIn Time, everything is forgotten.",
