    "message": "\n{{ name }},\n\nHoly shit, I'm pretty sure that I've had the exact same conversation with a friend of mine. We both came to the conclusion that no, we were not depressed, perhaps just disillusioned. We were sick of being \"passengers\" in our life. We are both young (24 and 27 years old), and felt that our contributions were simply doing nothing to make the world better, or really, just doing nothing at all. However, I feel that I'm doing something right by asking myself those two questions: \"how am I helping the world?\" and \"how am I going to be remembered?\"\n\nWell, it's hard when you're young and optimistic and you feel like you can expand your knowledge and influence ad infinitum. Hopefully, I've convinced you by now that I have and still sometimes feel this same way.\n\nSince I find generalized advice from people (especially on the Listserv) rarely actually means anything to how you live your day-to-day life, I'll just state the specific ways I've dealt with this feeling and hopefully it'll inspire your own solutions:\n\n    I quit my job where I felt like a cog in a very large machine. I now co-run my own business, helping small, local business grow (I'm sure you see this happen everyday, living in SF), which leads into my second action...\n\n    Started looking how I could have a local influence and help my fellow man in my own backyard: volunteering, teaching, whatever.\n\n    Stopped worrying on a cosmic (or even global) scale about my influence and mark on history: it only frustrated me and served to distract from my own goals.\n\n    I am religious, and no, I'm not trying to convert you; I'm just stating that It has helped me fill some of the gaps in that purposelessness.\n\nSome people say when you have children, that is the ultimate way to secure a legacy. I don't have kids yet so I can't speak to that. But, in the meantime, I'm just going to do my best to stop wasting energy worrying about these things and focus on the reality at hand.\n\nLastly, I read this article called, \"Just F*cking Do It\" the other day, and it really challenged me. Maybe it'll help you too. Good luck finding your place.",
    "cleaned": true,
    "title": "This Exact Conversation",
    "quote": "I stopped worrying on a cosmic (or even global) scale about my influence and mark on history: it only frustrated me and served to distract from my own goals.",
    "position": 104
