    "subject": "\"Your ListServe message, and some somewhat-unsolic\"",
    "tags": [
      "Passion"
    ],
    "message": "I've reached the ripe old age of 32, and I've had somewhat similar problems to yours, though from a different perspective. \n\nI mention my website first and foremost because it ties in to all of this. Do you remember Kindergarten? The earliest \"career day\" when you sat around and talked about what you wanted to be when you grew up? An astronaut, a fireman, the president, a mermaid... I have an uncle who served as my \"father figure\", as it were, and he was into computers when they were just starting to enter the home, so I'd been around some kind of technology for my entire life - five whole years as of that point. He was also kind of a kid at heart - we had all of the video game systems out at the time. (Boy, I wish I still had that collection!) I knew way back then that I wanted to make video games - it just seemed like the neatest thing ever.\n\nI've never really wavered from that, either. \n\nI spent the time I was growing up being told a handful of things that were probably intended to assist on the path - oh, you'll need to go to college for that, get a job as a tester and work your way up, you have to follow the most recent trends, etc. - but they all seemed to be missing something. This is akin to biology or music in a specific way - if you do look at my website, I did it. I am almost, after many years, at the point where my hobby pays its own expenses. I cannot honestly say I make any notable profit from it, and definitely not a living. I've got a grunt-labor job that almost covers the bills, and I make up the difference in odd-job design and video editing - but by golly, I made games. I'm still making games.\n\nI never wanted to \"get into the games industry\". My goal was not to \"get a job making games\". It sounds dumb, but stripped to its most basic, I wanted to make games. (I also wanted to play guitar. For my 21st birthday, I bought a guitar. I played with it until I figured out how to play to my own satisfaction.)\n\nI suppose my point is, it seems almost like a fear of your own mortality is creeping in and standing between you and the things you are genuinely passionate about. I know that it seems that there will be something keeping you from having any lasting impact in the world after you aren't here to continue to help it grow and learn. Here's an odd piece of trivia, though, that might help put things into perspective - I know it's helped me before, if nothing else by making me chuckle.\n\nWe're coming up steadily on the fiftieth anniversary of Woodstock. Summer of Love, all of that noise. The year that brought us seminal performances, memorable for a lifetime and beyond. A generation that, in many ways, reinvented rock and roll. Jimi Hendrix! The star-spangled banner on guitar, with feedback as an instrument! Pete Townsend singing out to a rising sun, \"Listening to You, I get the music...\"\n\nAll of this cultural redefinition. A generation rising almost in unison. And the Billboard number one selling single that year?\n\n\"Sugar Sugar\", by the Archies.\n\nNobody knows until it's far too late what's going to really matter - and it's very rarely what people expect at any time. Posthumous glory is never lauded on the living.\n\nIf you want to make music, make music. Make it for you. Make it for the people you love. Someone will hear it. Technology and progress and cultural shifts be damned - if you have something to share, share it. Someone will find and appreciate it. We're at a point now where very little is TRULY ephemeral - the world is an ever growing archive. Sing to yourself. Sing to me. But if you genuinely feel it, do it.\n\n(Forgive my mangling of grammar, but I'm twisting words to emphasize a point)\n\nIf you want to biology, then biology. Don't worry about \"being a biologist\". Learn. Grow. Share your knowledge. Tutor people - and find the most difficult ones you can, the ones who ask \"Why?\" until they drive you back to the books. Write down what you know. Write down what you think. Pass it along to everyone you know with any interest in the field. Hell, let me proofread papers you write just because you are passionate about sharing what you already know - even if other people already know it too. But don't let the \"real world\" interfere with doing something you are passionate about.\n\nIf you have lost sight of things, then do SOMETHING. Do ANYTHING. Find something that becomes a passion for you - regardless of its practicality, or purpose, or chance of lasting forever. Do something that becomes (in a positive way - I advise against heroin, for example) all-consuming. Something that you just cannot picture yourself not doing. Having access to that passion in your life can become a reason to exist unto itself. Don't deny it just because it doesn't feel permanent right now.\n\nFeeling like an observer in your own life is (in my opinion) not ENTIRELY removed from the truth. You have a choice, though - you can be \"merely\" an observer, or you can be a participant. You can't always be the sole driver, but you don't have to be just a passenger. There's no guarantee that what you do will change the world forever, but there's also no guarantee that it won't, just a fear.\n\nSilly Putty was invented by accident, after all. Rather than throw away a failed synthetic rubber, they turned it into something else - and the chemist that produced it kept on chemistry-ing. That was \"his thing\" - it was \"what he did\".\n\nAnyway, enough rambling. This is my first response to something I've read on Listserve, and I hope I didn't bungle it too badly or say nothing at all of help or substance. Feel free to ignore me, or write me back, or curse my name, or check out my games, or what have you. But... Do the things you want to do. Don't let fear of the future stop you, or slow you down. I'll be cheering for you the whole time.\n\nYours,",
